  "why": "The BET method explicitly constrains all mutations relative to the original seed (not only relative to the immediate previous mutant) by fixing each perturbation magnitude to ±ε and by enforcing an overall L∞ bound. The mutator logic always references the original input Eo when choosing a byte's value (bytes are toggled between Eo, Eo+ε, or Eo-ε), so cumulative distortion beyond the chosen ε is prevented. Additionally, perturbations are applied as integer pixel changes (avoiding continuous→discrete inversion issues) and an explicit L∞ budget (13/255) is used. Together these design choices both preserve semantic consistency (pixels never drift beyond the allowed semantic-preserving bound from the original) and maintain naturalness/realism (small bounded pixel changes, integer-valued), satisfying the metric's requirements for “High.”",
  "evidence": "Section 3.1 (Key Insight) and Section 3.5 (Mutator / Perturbation values) — \"For simplicity, we fixate the absolute value of ˆδi as ε in BET, and try to find proper signs to maximize Dif.\" (page 5, Section 3.1). \"Instead, we limit the perturbations to each byte to two choices {+ε, −ε}, where ε is a hyperparameter specific to application scenarios. Then, the search space of perturbations greatly reduces to 2^N.\" and \"Given an original input Eo, a current best test case Eb derived from it, and a slice to add perturbations, we examine each byte in the slice and add perturbations accordingly. Assuming the byte being examined is the i-th byte in the test case if Eb[i] = Eo[i], we randomly add perturbation value of +ε or −ε to this byte. If Eb[i] = Eo[i] − ε, we change this byte to Eo[i] + ε. Otherwise, Eb[i] = Eo[i] + ε must hold and we change this byte to Eo[i] − ε.\" (page 7, Section 3.5). Section 4.1 (Hyperparameters) — \"We use the widely used L∞ metric ... we choose values that make them perform relatively well, i.e., L∞ = 13/255 on all datasets (all compared methods use the same setting).\" (page 8, Section 4.1). Section 4.3 (Inact-Rate discussion) — \"The Inact-Rate of BET is 0.0%. The perturbations are directly added on pixel values as integers, BET does not suffer the inactivation issue.\" (page 10, Section 4.3). These passages demonstrate per-byte ±ε bounds relative to the original seed, an overall L∞ constraint, and integer-valued perturbations that together prevent cumulative drift and preserve input plausibility."
